## (4)(b) Antenna Gain and Directivity

> Explain the concepts of antenna gain and directivity. *(5 marks)*

---

**Directivity**

How much an antenna focuses energy in a particular direction compared to an **isotropic antenna** (which radiates equally in all directions).

$$D = \frac{\text{Power density in max direction}}{\text{Average power density over all directions}}$$

- A flashlight has high directivity (focused beam)
- A light bulb has low directivity (radiates everywhere)

---

**Gain**

Gain = Directivity Ã— Efficiency

$$G = \eta \cdot D$$

Where $\eta$ is the antenna efficiency (accounts for resistive losses, mismatches).

- **Gain** tells you the *actual* amplification in the preferred direction
- **Directivity** is the *theoretical* maximum if there were no losses
- Both are measured in **dBi** (relative to isotropic antenna)

> A typical WiFi antenna has gain of 2-5 dBi. A cellular base station dish might have 15-20 dBi.

